               <p>JAMES ROBERTS DICKIE. I live in <placeName id="t18310630-249-crimeloc1313">Stanhope-street</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18310630-249-crimeloc1313" type="placeName" value="Stanhope-street"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18310630-249-crimeloc1313" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18310630-249-off1311 t18310630-249-crimeloc1313"></join>. - On the 28th of June, about a quarter to ten o'clock in the morning, this umbrella and cloak were in my chaise, which stood at my door - I am a <rs id="t18310630-249-viclabel1314" type="occupation">traveller</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18310630-249-victim1818 t18310630-249-viclabel1314"></join>; I was absent four or five minutes, and when I came down to get into the chaise<xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183106300117"></xptr>a man, who was repairing the road, said "Is not that your cloak, Sir?" I looked into the chaise, and it was gone - I saw the prisoner walking away very deliberately with my cloak and umbrella - I followed, and took him at the corner of the street with them, apparently intoxicated, but whether it was sham I do not know; I said, "My friend, I thank you for the trouble you have taken, but these are mine;" he turned round, and said, "Which is Holles-street?" I gave him in charge.(Property produced and sworn to.)</p>
               <p>
            
